\subsection{Bevölkerungszahlen}

\subsubsection{Quelle}

<<echo=FALSE>>=
# output = ['area', 'year', 'sex', 'age', 'population']
colCls <- c("character", "integer", "factor", "factor", "numeric")

p <- read.csv("./population/040-csv-for-r/population.csv",
  colClasses = colCls)
@

Quelle: \url{http://esa.un.org/wpp/Excel-Data/population.htm} \Rightarrow ``Annual Population by Age Groups''. United Nations, Department of Economic and Social Affairs, Population Division (2013). World Population Prospects: The 2012 Revision, CD-ROM Edition.

Unter \url{http://esa.un.org/wpp/index.htm} ist einsehbar, auf welchen Quellen die Bevölkerungszahlen im Detail beruhen.

Beispiele, gerechnet auf Basis der Daten:


<<echo=FALSE>>=

f <- function(n) {
  return(format(n, big.mark = "'"))
  # return(formatC(n, format = "f", digits = 3, big.mark = "'", decimal.mark = ","))
}

pop_2000 = sum(p[p$area == "WORLD" & p$year == 2000, c("population")]) * 1000

pop_2010 = sum(p[p$area == "WORLD" & p$year == 2010, c("population")]) * 1000

pop_2000_to_2010_yearly_growth = ((pop_2010 / pop_2000) ^ (1/10) - 1) * 100

@

Weltbevölkerung in 2000: \Sexpr{esc(f(pop_2000))}

Weltbevölkerung in 2010: \Sexpr{esc(f(pop_2010))}

% Rein mathematischer jährlicher, exponentieller Zuwachs von 2000 zu 2010:

Durchschnittliches jährliches Wachstum: \Sexpr{round(pop_2000_to_2010_yearly_growth, 3)}\%

Kontrolle:

$$
\Sexpr{round(pop_2000)} \cdot ( \frac{\Sexpr{round(pop_2000_to_2010_yearly_growth, 8)}}{100} + 1 )^{10} = \Sexpr{round(pop_2000 * (pop_2000_to_2010_yearly_growth/100 + 1) ^ 10)}
$$


